# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hitachi-ibaraki
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 11 March 2011, at 14:46:24 JST (05:46:24 UTC), a Mw 9.0–9.1 undersea megathrust earthquake occurred in the Pacific Ocean, 72 km (45 mi) east of the Oshika Peninsula of the Tōhoku region of Japan.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It lasted approximately six minutes and caused a tsunami.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It is sometimes known in Japan as the "**Great East Japan Earthquake**" (東日本大震災, *Higashi Nihon Daishinsai*), among other names.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It is often referred to by its numerical date, **3.11** (read *San ten Ichi-ichi* in Japanese).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake was the most powerful ever recorded in Japan, and the fourth most powerful recorded in the world since modern seismography began in 1900.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It triggered powerful tsunami waves that may have reached heights of up to 40.5 meters (133 ft) in Miyako in Tōhoku's Iwate Prefecture, and which, in the Sendai area, traveled at 700 km/h (435 mph) and up to 10 km (6 mi) inland.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Residents of Sendai had only eight to ten minutes of warning, and more than a hundred evacuation sites were washed away.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The snowfall which accompanied the tsunami and the freezing temperature hindered rescue works; for instance, in Ishinomaki, the city with the most deaths, the temperature was 0 °C (32 °F) as the tsunami hit.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Official figures released in 2021 reported 19,759 deaths, 6,242 injured, 284 firefighters dead from attempts to close preventative fire gates, and 2,553 missing.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A report in 2015 found that 228,863 people were still living away from their home either temporarily or permanently.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami caused the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster, primarily the meltdowns of three of its reactors, the discharge of radioactive water in Fukushima and the associated evacuation zones affecting hundreds of thousands of residents.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Many electrical generators ran out of fuel.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The loss of electrical power halted cooling systems, causing heat to build.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Without ventilation, hydrogen gas accumulated within the upper refueling hall and exploded, forcefully ejecting the refueling hall's blast panels.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Residents within a 20 km (12 mi) radius of the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant and a 10 km (6.2 mi) radius of the Fukushima Daini Nuclear Power Plant were evacuated.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Early estimates placed insured losses from the earthquake alone at US$14.5 to $34.6 billion.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Bank of Japan offered ¥15 trillion (US$183 billion) to the banking system on 14 March 2011 in an effort to normalize market conditions.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The estimated economic damage amounted to over $300 billion, making it the costliest natural disaster in history.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] According to a 2020 study, "the earthquake and its aftermaths resulted in a 0.47 percentage point decline in Japan's real GDP growth in the year following the disaster".
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake was initially reported as 7.9 Mw by the USGS before it was quickly upgraded to 8.8 Mw, then to 8.9 Mw, and then finally to 9.0 Mw.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 11 July 2016, the USGS further upgraded the earthquake to 9.1.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Sendai was the nearest major city to the earthquake, 130 km (81 mi) from the epicenter; the earthquake occurred 373 km (232 mi) northeast of Tokyo.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The main earthquake was preceded by a number of large foreshocks, with hundreds of aftershocks reported.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One of the first major foreshocks was a 7.2 Mw event on 9 March, approximately 40 km (25 mi) from the epicenter of the 11 March earthquake, with another three on the same day in excess of 6.0 Mw.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Following the main earthquake on 11 March, a 7.4 Mw aftershock was reported at 15:08 JST (6:06 UTC), succeeded by a 7.9 Mw at 15:15 JST (6:16 UTC) and a 7.7 Mw at 15:26 JST (6:26 UTC).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Over 800 aftershocks of magnitude 4.5 Mw or greater occurred after the initial quake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Aftershocks followed Omori's law, which states that the rate of aftershocks declines with the reciprocal of the time since the main quake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The aftershocks thus tapered off over time, but continued for years after the initial quake, including one on 26 October 2013 (local time) of magnitude 7.1 Mw.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Initially, the earthquake caused part of Honshu's Pacific coast to sink by roughly a meter, but after about three years, the coast rose back and then kept on rising to exceed its original height.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This megathrust earthquake was a recurrence of the mechanism of the earlier 869 Sanriku earthquake, which has been estimated as having a magnitude of at least 8.4 Mw, which also created a large tsunami that inundated the Sendai plain.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Three tsunami deposits have been identified within the Holocene sequence of the plain, all formed within the last 3,000 years, suggesting an 800 to 1,100 year recurrence interval for large tsunamigenic earthquakes.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In 2001 it was reckoned that there was a high likelihood of a large tsunami hitting the Sendai plain as more than 1,100 years had then elapsed.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In 2007, the probability of an earthquake with a magnitude of Mw 8.1–8.3 was estimated as 99% within the following 30 years.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This earthquake occurred where the Pacific plate is subducting under the plate beneath northern Honshu.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Pacific plate, which moves at a rate of 8 to 9 cm (3.1 to 3.5 in) per year, dips under Honshu's underlying plate, building large amounts of elastic energy.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This motion pushes the upper plate down until the accumulated stress causes a seismic slip-rupture event.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The break caused the sea floor to rise by several meters.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The magnitude of this earthquake was a surprise to some seismologists.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A quake of this magnitude usually has a rupture length of at least 500 km (310 mi) and generally requires a long, relatively straight fault surface.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Because the plate boundary and subduction zone in the area of the Honshu rupture is not very straight, it is unusual for the magnitude of its earthquake to exceed 8.5 Mw.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The hypocentral region of this earthquake extended from offshore Iwate Prefecture to offshore Ibaraki Prefecture.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Japan Meteorological Agency said that the earthquake may have ruptured the fault zone from Iwate to Ibaraki with a length of 500 km (310 mi) and a width of 200 km (120 mi).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Analysis showed that this earthquake consisted of a set of three events.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Other major earthquakes with tsunamis struck the Sanriku Coast region in 1896 and in 1933.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The source area of this earthquake has a relatively high coupling coefficient surrounded by areas of relatively low coupling coefficients in the west, north, and south.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The seismic moment of this earthquake accounts for about 93% of the estimated cumulative moment from 1926 to March 2011.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Hence, earthquakes in this area with magnitudes of about 7 since 1926 had only released part of the accumulated energy.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the area near the trench, the coupling coefficient is high, which could act as the source of the large tsunami.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Most of the foreshocks are interplate earthquakes with thrust-type focal mechanisms.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Both interplate and intraplate earthquakes appeared in the aftershocks offshore Sanriku coast with considerable proportions.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The surface energy of the seismic waves from the earthquake was calculated to be 1.9×1017 joules, which is nearly double that of the 9.1 Mw 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami that killed 230,000 people.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] If harnessed, the seismic energy from this earthquake would power a city the size of Los Angeles for an entire year.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The seismic moment (M0), which represents a physical size for the event, was calculated by the USGS at 3.9×1022 joules, slightly less than the 2004 Indian Ocean quake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The strong ground motion registered at the maximum of *Shindo* 7 on the Japan Meteorological Agency seismic intensity scale in Kurihara, Miyagi Prefecture.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Three other prefectures—Fukushima, Ibaraki and Tochigi—recorded a 6 upper on the JMA scale.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Seismic stations in Iwate, Gunma, Saitama and Chiba Prefectures measured a 6 lower, while Tokyo and five other prefectures recorded 5 upper.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Japan's National Research Institute for Earth Science and Disaster Prevention (NIED) calculated a peak ground acceleration of 2.99 *g* (29.33 m/s2).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Tremors from the earthquake were also felt in the Northern Mariana Islands, the Korean Peninsula, Taiwan, Northeast China and the Russian Far East.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Portions of northeastern Japan shifted by as much as 2.4 meters (7 ft 10 in) closer to North America, making some sections of Japan's landmass wider than before.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Those areas of Japan closest to the epicenter experienced the largest shifts.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 400-kilometer (250 mi) stretch of coastline dropped vertically by 0.6 meters (2 ft 0 in), allowing the tsunami to travel farther and faster onto land.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One early estimate suggested that the Pacific plate may have moved westward by up to 20 meters (66 ft), and another early estimate put the amount of slippage at as much as 40 m (130 ft).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 6 April, the Japanese coast guard said that the quake shifted the seabed near the epicenter 24 meters (79 ft) and elevated the seabed off the coast of Miyagi Prefecture by 3 meters (9.8 ft).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A report by the Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology, published in *Science* on 2 December 2011, concluded that the seabed in the area between the epicenter and the Japan Trench moved 50 meters (160 ft) east-southeast and rose about 7 meters (23 ft) as a result of the quake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The report also stated that the quake had caused several major landslides on the seabed in the affected area.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Earth's axis shifted by estimates of between 10 and 25 cm (4 and 10 in).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This deviation led to a number of small planetary changes, including the length of a day, the tilt of the Earth, and the Chandler wobble.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The speed of the Earth's rotation increased, shortening the day by 1.8 microseconds due to the redistribution of Earth's mass.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The axial shift was caused by the redistribution of mass on the Earth's surface, which changed the planet's moment of inertia.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Because of conservation of angular momentum, such changes of inertia result in small changes to the Earth's rate of rotation.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] These are expected changes for an earthquake of this magnitude.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake also generated infrasound waves detected by perturbations in the orbit of the GOCE satellite, which thus serendipitously became the first seismograph in orbit.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Following the earthquake, cracks were observed to have formed in the roof of Mount Fuji's magma chamber.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Seiches observed in Sognefjorden, Norway, were attributed to distant S waves and Love waves generated by the earthquake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] These seiches began to occur roughly half an hour after the main shock hit Japan, and continued to occur for 3 hours, during which waves of up to 1.5 meters high were observed.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Soil liquefaction was evident in areas of reclaimed land around Tokyo, particularly in Urayasu, Chiba City, Funabashi, Narashino (all in Chiba Prefecture) and in the Koto, Edogawa, Minato, Chūō, and Ōta wards of Tokyo.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Approximately 30 homes or buildings were destroyed and 1,046 other buildings were damaged to varying degrees.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Nearby Haneda Airport, built mostly on reclaimed land, was not damaged.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Odaiba also experienced liquefaction, but damage was minimal.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Shinmoedake, a volcano in Kyushu, erupted three days after the earthquake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The volcano had previously erupted in January 2011; it is not known if the later eruption was linked to the earthquake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In Antarctica, the seismic waves from the earthquake were reported to have caused the Whillans Ice Stream to slip by about 0.5 meters (1 ft 8 in).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The first sign international researchers had that the earthquake caused such a dramatic change in the Earth's rotation came from the United States Geological Survey which monitors Global Positioning Satellite (GPS) stations across the world.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Survey team had several GPS monitors located near the scene of the earthquake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The GPS station located nearest the epicenter moved almost 4 m (13 ft).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This motivated government researchers to look into other ways the earthquake may have had large scale effects on the planet.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Calculations at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory determined that the Earth's rotation was changed by the earthquake to the point where the days are now 1.8 microseconds shorter.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Japan experienced over 1,000 aftershocks since the earthquake, with 80 registering over magnitude 6.0 Mw and several of which have been over magnitude 7.0 Mw.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A month later, a major aftershock struck offshore on 7 April with a magnitude of 7.1 Mw.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Its epicenter was underwater, 66 km (41 mi) off the coast of Sendai.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Japan Meteorological Agency assigned a magnitude of 7.4 MJMA, while the United States Geological Survey lowered it to 7.1 Mw.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At least four people were killed, and electricity was cut off across much of northern Japan including the loss of external power to Higashidōri Nuclear Power Plant and Rokkasho Reprocessing Plant.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Four days later on 11 April, another magnitude 7.1 Mw aftershock struck Fukushima, causing additional damage and killing a total of three people.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 7 December 2012 a large aftershock of magnitude 7.3 Mw caused a minor tsunami, and again on 26 October 2013 a small tsunami was recorded after a 7.1 Mw aftershock.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As of 16 March 2012 aftershocks continued, totaling 1887 events over magnitude 4.0; a regularly updated map showing all shocks of magnitude 4.5 and above near or off the east coast of Honshu in the last seven days showed over 20 events.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As of 11 March 2016 there had been 869 aftershocks of 5.0 Mw or greater, 118 of 6.0 Mw or greater, and 9 over 7.0 Mw as reported by the Japan Meteorological Agency.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The number of aftershocks was associated with decreased health across Japan.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 13 February 2021, a magnitude 7.1–7.3 earthquake struck off the coast of Sendai.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It caused some damage in Miyagi and Fukushima prefectures.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One person was killed, and 185 were injured.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Geospatial Information Authority of Japan reported land subsidence based on the height of triangulation stations in the area measured by GPS as compared to their previous values from 14 April 2011.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Scientists say that the subsidence is permanent.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As a result, the communities in question are now more susceptible to flooding during high tides.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One minute before the earthquake was felt in Tokyo, the Earthquake Early Warning system, which includes more than 1,000 seismometers in Japan, sent out warnings of impending strong shaking to millions.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It is believed that the early warning by the Japan Meteorological Agency (JMA) saved many lives.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The warning for the general public was delivered about eight seconds after the first P wave was detected, or about 31 seconds after the earthquake occurred.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, the estimated intensities were smaller than the actual ones in some places, especially in Kanto, Koshinetsu, and Northern Tōhoku regions where the populace warning did not trigger.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] There were also cases where large differences between estimated intensities by the Earthquake Early Warning system and the actual intensities occurred in the aftershocks and triggered earthquakes.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Such discrepancies in the warning were attributed by the JMA to the system's inability to distinguish between two different earthquakes that happened at around same time, as well as to the reduced number of reporting seismometers due to power outages and connection failures.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The system's software was subsequently modified to handle this kind of situation.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] An upthrust of 6 to 8 meters (20 to 26 ft) along a 180-kilometer (110 mi)-wide seabed at 60 kilometers (37 mi) offshore from the east coast of Tōhoku resulted in a major tsunami that brought destruction along the Pacific coastline of Japan's northern islands.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Thousands of people died and entire towns were devastated.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami propagated throughout the Pacific Ocean region reaching the entire Pacific coast of North and South America from Alaska to Chile.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Warnings were issued and evacuations were carried out in many countries bordering the Pacific.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Although the tsunami affected many of these places, the heights of the waves were minor.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Chile's Pacific coast, one of the farthest from Japan at about 17,000 kilometers (11,000 mi) away, was struck by waves 2 meters (6.6 ft) high, compared with an estimated wave height of 38.9 meters (128 ft) at Omoe peninsula, Miyako city, Japan.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami warning issued by the Japan Meteorological Agency was the most serious on its warning scale; it was rated as a "major tsunami", being at least 3 meters (9.8 ft) high.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The actual height prediction varied, the greatest being for Miyagi at 6 meters (20 ft) high.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami inundated a total area of approximately 561 square kilometers (217 sq mi) in Japan.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At 15:55 JST, a tsunami was observed flooding Sendai Airport, which is located near the coast of Miyagi Prefecture, with waves sweeping away cars and planes and flooding various buildings as they traveled inland.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The impact of the tsunami in and around Sendai Airport was filmed by an NHK News helicopter, showing a number of vehicles on local roads trying to escape the approaching wave and being engulfed by it.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 4-meter-high (13 ft) tsunami hit Iwate Prefecture.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Wakabayashi Ward in Sendai was also particularly hard hit.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At least 101 designated tsunami evacuation sites were hit by the wave.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Like the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami, the damage by surging water, though much more localized, was far more deadly and destructive than the actual quake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Entire towns were destroyed in tsunami-hit areas in Japan, including 9,500 missing in Minamisanriku; one thousand bodies had been recovered in the town by 14 March 2011.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Among the factors in the high death toll was the unexpectedly large water surge.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The sea walls in several cities had been built to protect against tsunamis of much lower heights.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also, many people caught in the tsunami thought they were on high enough ground to be safe.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] According to a special committee on disaster prevention designated by the Japanese government, the tsunami protection policy had been intended to deal with only tsunamis that had been scientifically proved to occur repeatedly.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The committee advised that future policy should be to protect against the highest possible tsunami.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Because tsunami walls had been overtopped, the committee also suggested, besides building taller tsunami walls, also teaching citizens how to evacuate if a large-scale tsunami should strike.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Large parts of Kuji and the southern section of Ōfunato including the port area were almost entirely destroyed.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also largely destroyed was Rikuzentakata, where the tsunami was three stories high.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Other cities destroyed or heavily damaged by the tsunami include Kamaishi, Miyako, Ōtsuchi, and Yamada (in Iwate Prefecture), Namie, Sōma, and Minamisōma (in Fukushima Prefecture) and Shichigahama, Higashimatsushima, Onagawa, Natori, Ishinomaki, and Kesennuma (in Miyagi Prefecture).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The most severe effects of the tsunami were felt along a 670-kilometer-long (420 mi) stretch of coastline from Erimo, Hokkaido, in the north to Ōarai, Ibaraki, in the south, with most of the destruction in that area occurring in the hour following the earthquake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Near Ōarai, people captured images of a huge whirlpool that had been generated by the tsunami.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami washed away the sole bridge to Miyatojima, Miyagi, isolating the island's 900 residents.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 2 meters (6 ft 7 in) high tsunami hit Chiba Prefecture about 2+1⁄2 hours after the quake, causing heavy damage to cities such as Asahi.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 13 March 2011, the Japan Meteorological Agency (JMA) published details of tsunami observations recorded around the coastline of Japan following the earthquake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The bulletin also included initial tsunami observation details, as well as more detailed maps for the coastlines affected by the tsunami waves.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami at Ryōri Bay (綾里湾), Ōfunato reached a height of 40.1 meters (132 ft) (run-up elevation).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Fishing equipment was scattered on the high cliff above the bay.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At Tarō, Iwate, the tsunami reached a height of 37.9 meters (124 ft) up the slope of a mountain some 200 meters (660 ft) away from the coastline.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also, at the slope of a nearby mountain from 400 meters (1,300 ft) away at Aneyoshi fishery port (姉吉漁港) of Omoe peninsula (重茂半島) in Miyako, Iwate, Tokyo University of Marine Science and Technology found estimated tsunami run up height of 38.9 meters (128 ft).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This height is deemed the record in Japan historically, as of reporting date, that exceeds 38.2 meters (125 ft) from the 1896 Sanriku earthquake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It was also estimated that the tsunami reached heights of up to 40.5 meters (133 ft) in Miyako in Tōhoku's Iwate Prefecture.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The inundated areas closely matched those of the 869 Sanriku tsunami.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Inundation heights were observed along 2,000 kilometers (1,200 mi) of the coast from Hokkaido to Kyushu in a 2012 study.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Maximum run-up heights greater than 10 meters (33 ft) were distributed along 530 kilometers (330 mi) of coast, and maximum run-up heights greater than 20 meters (66 ft) were distributed along 200 kilometers (120 mi) of the coast, measured directly.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami resulted in significant erosion of the Rikuzen-Takata coastline, mainly caused by backwash.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 2016 study indicated that the coast has not naturally recovered at a desirable rate since the tsunami.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A Japanese government study found that 58% of people in coastal areas in Iwate, Miyagi, and Fukushima prefectures heeded tsunami warnings immediately after the quake and headed for higher ground.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Of those who attempted to evacuate after hearing the warning, only five percent were caught in the tsunami.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Of those who did not heed the warning, 49% were hit by the water.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Delayed evacuations in response to the warnings had a number of causes.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami height that had been initially predicted by the tsunami warning system was lower than the actual tsunami height; this error contributed to the delayed escape of some residents.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The discrepancy arose as follows: in order to produce a quick prediction of a tsunami's height and thus to provide a timely warning, the initial earthquake and tsunami warning that was issued for the event was based on a calculation that requires only about three minutes.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This calculation is, in turn, based on the maximum amplitude of the seismic wave.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The amplitude of the seismic wave is measured using the JMA magnitude scale, which is similar to Richter scale.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, these scales "saturate" for earthquakes that are above a certain magnitude (magnitude 8 on the JMA scale); that is, in the case of very large earthquakes, the scales' values change little despite large differences in the earthquakes' energy.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This resulted in an underestimation of the tsunami's height in initial reports.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Problems in issuing updates also contributed to delays in evacuations.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The warning system was supposed to be updated about 15 minutes after the earthquake occurred, by which time the calculation for the moment magnitude scale would normally be completed.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, the strong quake had exceeded the measurement limit of all of the teleseismometers within Japan, and thus it was impossible to calculate the moment magnitude based on data from those seismometers.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Another cause of delayed evacuations was the release of the second update on the tsunami warning long after the earthquake (28 minutes, according to observations); by that time, power failures and similar circumstances reportedly prevented the update from reaching some residents.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also, observed data from tidal meters that were located off the coast were not fully reflected in the second warning.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In response to the aforementioned shortcomings in the tsunami warning system, JMA began an investigation in 2011 and updated their system in 2013.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the updated system, for a powerful earthquake that is capable of causing the JMA magnitude scale to saturate, no quantitative prediction will be released in the initial warning; instead, there will be words that describe the situation's emergency.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] There are plans to install new teleseismometers with the ability to measure larger earthquakes, which would allow the calculation of a quake's moment magnitude scale in a timely manner.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] JMA also implemented a simpler empirical method to integrate, into a tsunami warning, data from GPS tidal meters as well as from undersea water pressure meters, and there are plans to install more of these meters and to develop further technology to utilize data observed by them.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] To prevent under-reporting of tsunami heights, early quantitative observation data that are smaller than the expected amplitude will be overridden and the public will instead be told that the situation is under observation.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] About 90 seconds after an earthquake, an additional report on the possibility of a tsunami will also be included in observation reports, in order to warn people before the JMA magnitude can be calculated.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Pacific Tsunami Warning Center (PTWC) in Hawaii issued tsunami watches and announcements for locations in the Pacific.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At 07:30 UTC, PTWC issued a widespread tsunami warning covering the entire Pacific Ocean.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Russia evacuated 11,000 residents from coastal areas of the Kuril Islands.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The United States National Tsunami Warning Center issued a tsunami warning for the coastal areas in most of California, all of Oregon, and the western part of Alaska, and a tsunami advisory covering the Pacific coastlines of most of Alaska, and all of Washington and British Columbia, Canada.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In California and Oregon, up to 2.4 m-high (7.9 ft) tsunami waves hit some areas, damaging docks and harbors and causing over US$10 million in damage.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In Curry County, Oregon, US$7 million in damage occurred including the destruction of 1,100 m (3,600 ft) of docks at the Brookings harbor; the county received over US$1 million in FEMA emergency grants from the US Federal Government.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Surges of up to 1 m (3 ft 3 in) hit Vancouver Island in Canada prompting some evacuations, and causing boats to be banned from the waters surrounding the island for 12 hours following the wave strike, leaving many island residents in the area without means of getting to work.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the Philippines, waves up to 0.5 m (1 ft 8 in) high hit the eastern seaboard of the country.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Some houses along the coast in Jayapura, Indonesia were destroyed.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Authorities in Wewak, East Sepik, Papua New Guinea evacuated 100 patients from the city's Boram Hospital before it was hit by waves, causing an estimated US$4 million in damage.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Hawaii estimated damage to public infrastructure alone at US$3 million, with damage to private properties, including resort hotels such as Four Seasons Resort Hualalai, estimated at tens of millions of dollars.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It was reported that a 1.5 m-high (4.9 ft) wave completely submerged Midway Atoll's reef inlets and Spit Island, killing more than 110,000 nesting seabirds at the Midway Atoll National Wildlife Refuge.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Some other South Pacific countries, including Tonga and New Zealand, and US territories American Samoa and Guam, experienced larger-than-normal waves, but did not report any major damage.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, in Guam some roads were closed off and people were evacuated from low-lying areas.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Along the Pacific Coast of Mexico and South America, tsunami surges were reported, but in most places caused little or no damage.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Peru reported a wave of 1.5 m (4 ft 11 in) and more than 300 homes damaged.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The surge in Chile was large enough to damage more than 200 houses, with waves of up to 3 m (9.8 ft).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the Galápagos Islands, 260 families received assistance following a 3 m (9.8 ft) surge which arrived 20 hours after the earthquake, after the tsunami warning had been lifted.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] There was a great deal of damage to buildings on the islands and one man was injured but there were no reported fatalities.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami broke icebergs off the Sulzberger Ice Shelf in Antarctica, 13,000 km (8,100 mi) away.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The main iceberg measured 9.5 km × 6.5 km (5.9 mi × 4.0 mi) (approximately the area of Manhattan Island) and about 80 m (260 ft) thick.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A total of 125 km2 (48 sq mi; 31,000 acres) of ice broke away.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As of April 2012, wreckage from the tsunami spread around the world, including a soccer ball which was found in Alaska's Middleton Island and a Japanese motorcycle found in British Columbia, Canada.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On the day of the earthquake, the waters of several fjords across Norway appeared to seethe as if boiling, and formed waves that rolled onto shores, most prominently in Sognefjorden, where the phenomenon was caught on film.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] After two years of research into the incidents in Norway, scientists concluded that the seismic energy of the earthquake generated seiche waves thousands of kilometers away.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The official figures released in 2021 reported 19,759 deaths, 6,242 injured, and 2,553 missing.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There were 10,567 deaths in Miyagi, 5,145 in Iwate, 3,920 in Fukushima, 66 in Ibaraki, 22 in Chiba, eight in Tokyo, six in Kanagawa, four in Tochigi, three each in Aomori and Yamagata, and one each in Gunma, Saitama and Hokkaido.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The leading causes of death were drowning (90.64% or 14,308 bodies), burning (0.9% or 145 bodies) and others (4.2% or 667 bodies, mostly crushed by heavy objects).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Injuries related to nuclear exposure or the discharge of radioactive water in Fukushima are difficult to trace as 60% of the 20,000 workers on-site declined to participate in state-sponsored free health checks.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Elderly aged over 60 account for 65.8% of all deaths, as shown on the table to the right.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A few cases of suicide are also included.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most of these deaths occurred during the first six months after the earthquake and the number dropped thereafter, but as time has passed, the number has continued to increase.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most of these deaths occurred in Fukushima Prefecture, where the prefectural government has suggested that they could be due to evacuations caused by the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Within Fukushima Prefecture, these indirect casualties have already resulted in more deaths than the number of people killed directly by earthquake and tsunami.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Save the Children reports that as many as 100,000 children were uprooted from their homes, some of whom were separated from their families because the earthquake occurred during the school day.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] 236 children were orphaned in the prefectures of Iwate, Miyagi and Fukushima by the disaster; 1,580 children lost either one or both parents, 846 in Miyagi, 572 in Iwate, and 162 in Fukushima.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The quake and tsunami killed 378 elementary, middle-school, and high school students and left 158 others missing.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] One elementary school in Ishinomaki, Miyagi, Okawa Elementary School, lost 74 of 108 students and 10 of 13 teachers in the tsunami due to poor decision making in evacuation.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Japanese Foreign Ministry confirmed the deaths of nineteen foreigners.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Among them were two English teachers from the United States affiliated with the Japan Exchange and Teaching Program; a Canadian missionary in Shiogama; and citizens of China, North and South Korea, Taiwan, Pakistan and the Philippines.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] By 9:30 UTC on 11 March 2011, Google Person Finder, which was previously used in the Haitian, Chilean, and Christchurch, New Zealand earthquakes, was collecting information about survivors and their locations.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japanese funerals are normally elaborate Buddhist ceremonies that entail cremation.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The thousands of bodies, however, exceeded the capacity of available crematoriums and morgues, many of them damaged, and there were shortages of both kerosene—each cremation requires 50 litres—and dry ice for preservation.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The single crematorium in Higashimatsushima, for example, could only handle four bodies a day, although hundreds were found there.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Governments and the military were forced to bury many bodies in hastily dug mass graves with rudimentary or no rites, although relatives of the deceased were promised that they would be cremated later.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of 27 May 2011, three Japan Ground Self-Defense Force members had died while conducting relief operations in Tōhoku.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of March 2012, the Japanese government had recognized 1,331 deaths as indirectly related to the earthquake, such as caused by harsh living conditions after the disaster.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of 30 April 2012, 18 people had died and 420 had been injured while participating in disaster recovery or clean-up efforts.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami was reported to have caused several deaths outside Japan.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] One man was killed in Jayapura, Papua, Indonesia after being swept out to sea.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A man who is said to have been attempting to photograph the oncoming tsunami at the mouth of the Klamath River, south of Crescent City, California, was swept out to sea.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] His body was found on 2 April 2011 along Ocean Beach in Fort Stevens State Park, Oregon, 530 km (330 mi) to the north.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The degree and extent of damage caused by the earthquake and resulting tsunami were enormous, with most of the damage being caused by the tsunami.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Video footage of the towns that were worst affected shows little more than piles of rubble, with almost no parts of any structures left standing.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Estimates of the cost of the damage range well into the tens of billions of US dollars; before-and-after satellite photographs of devastated regions show immense damage.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Although Japan has invested the equivalent of billions of dollars on anti-tsunami seawalls which line at least 40% of its 34,751 km (21,593 mi) coastline and stand up to 12 m (39 ft) high, the tsunami simply washed over the top of some seawalls, collapsing some in the process.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japan's National Police Agency said on 3 April 2011, that 45,700 buildings were destroyed and 144,300 were damaged by the quake and tsunami.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The damaged buildings included 29,500 structures in Miyagi Prefecture, 12,500 in Iwate Prefecture and 2,400 in Fukushima Prefecture.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Three hundred hospitals with 20 beds or more in Tōhoku were damaged by the disaster, with 11 being completely destroyed.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The earthquake and tsunami created an estimated 24–25 million tons of rubble and debris in Japan.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A report by the National Police Agency of Japan on 10 September 2018 listed 121,778 buildings as "total collapsed", with a further 280,926 buildings "half collapsed", and another 699,180 buildings "partially damaged".
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The earthquake and tsunami also caused extensive and severe structural damage in north-eastern Japan, including heavy damage to roads and railways as well as fires in many areas, and a dam collapse.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japanese Prime Minister Naoto Kan said, "In the 65 years after the end of World War II, this is the toughest and the most difficult crisis for Japan." Around 4.4 million households in northeastern Japan were left without electricity and 1.5 million without water.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] An estimated 230,000 automobiles and trucks were damaged or destroyed in the disaster.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of the end of May 2011, residents of Iwate, Miyagi, and Fukushima prefectures had requested the deregistration of 15,000 vehicles, meaning that the owners of those vehicles were writing them off as unrepairable or unsalvageable.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Low temperature and snowfall were major concerns after the earthquake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Snow arrived minutes before or after the tsunami, depending on locations.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Ishinomaki, the city which suffered the most deaths, a temperature of 0 °C (32 °F) was measured, and it began to snow within a couple of hours of the earthquake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Major snow fell again on 16 March, and intermittently in the coming weeks.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] 18 March was the coldest of that month, recording −4 to 6 °C (25 to 43 °F) in Sendai.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Photos of city ruins covered with snow were featured in various photo albums in international media, including NASA.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami produced huge amounts of debris: estimates of 5 million tonnes of waste were reported by the Japanese Ministry of the Environment.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Some of this waste, mostly plastic and styrofoam, washed up on the coasts of Canada and the United States in late 2011.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Along the west coast of the United States, this increased the amount of litter by a factor of ten and may have transported alien species.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All of Japan's ports were briefly shut down after the earthquake, though the ones in Tokyo and southwards soon re-opened.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Fifteen ports were located in the disaster zone.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The north eastern ports of Hachinohe, Sendai, Ishinomaki and Onahama were destroyed, while the Port of Chiba (which serves the hydrocarbon industry) and Japan's ninth-largest container port at Kashima were also affected, though less severely.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The ports at Hitachinaka, Hitachi, Soma, Shiogama, Kesennuma, Ofunato, Kamashi and Miyako were also damaged and closed to ships.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All 15 ports reopened to limited ship traffic by 29 March 2011.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A total of 319 fishing ports, about 10% of Japan's fishing ports, were damaged in the disaster.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most were restored to operating condition by 18 April 2012.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Port of Tokyo suffered slight damage; the effects of the quake included visible smoke rising from a building in the port with parts of the port areas being flooded, including soil liquefaction in Tokyo Disneyland's parking lot.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Fujinuma irrigation dam in Sukagawa ruptured, causing flooding and the washing away of five homes.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Eight people were missing and four bodies were discovered by the morning.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Reportedly, some locals had attempted to repair leaks in the dam before it completely failed.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On 12 March 252 dams were inspected and it was discovered that six embankment dams had shallow cracks on their crests.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The reservoir at one concrete gravity dam suffered a small non-serious slope failure.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All damaged dams are functioning with no problems.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Four dams within the quake area were unreachable.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In the immediate aftermath of the calamity, at least 1.5 million households were reported to have lost access to water supplies.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] By 21 March 2011, this number fell to 1.04 million.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] According to the Japanese trade ministry, around 4.4 million households served by Tōhoku Electric Power (TEP) in northeastern Japan were left without electricity.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Several nuclear and conventional power plants went offline, reducing the Tokyo Electric Power Company's (TEPCO) total capacity by 21 GW.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Rolling blackouts began on 14 March due to power shortages caused by the earthquake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] TEPCO, which normally provides approximately 40 GW of electricity, announced that it could only provide about 30 GW, because 40% of the electricity used in the greater Tokyo area was supplied by reactors in the Niigata and Fukushima prefectures.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The reactors at the Fukushima Daiichi and Fukushima Dai-ni plants were automatically taken offline when the first earthquake occurred and sustained major damage from the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Rolling blackouts of approximately three hours were experienced throughout April and May while TEPCO scrambled to find a temporary power solution.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The blackouts affected Tokyo, Kanagawa, Eastern Shizuoka, Yamanashi, Chiba, Ibaraki, Saitama, Tochigi, and Gunma prefectures.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Voluntary reductions in electricity use by consumers in the Kanto area helped reduce the predicted frequency and duration of the blackouts.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] By 21 March 2011, the number of households in the north without electricity fell to 242,927.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tōhoku Electric Power was not able to provide the Kanto region with additional power because TEP's power plants were also damaged in the earthquake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Two substations, one in Shizuoka Prefecture and one in Nagano Prefecture, were able to convert between frequencies and transfer electricity from Kansai to Kanto and Tōhoku, but their capacity was limited to 1 GW.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] With damage to so many power plants, it was feared it might be years before a long-term solution could be found.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] To help alleviate the shortage, three steel manufacturers in the Kanto region contributed electricity produced by their in-house conventional power stations to TEPCO for distribution to the general public.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Sumitomo Metal Industries could produce up to 500 MW, JFE Steel 400 MW, and Nippon Steel 500 MW of electric power.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Auto and auto parts makers in Kanto and Tōhoku agreed in May 2011 to operate their factories on Saturdays and Sundays and close on Thursdays and Fridays to help alleviate electricity shortages during the summer of 2011.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The public and other companies were also encouraged to conserve electricity in the 2011 summer months (Setsuden).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The expected electricity crisis in 2011 summer was successfully prevented thanks to all the *setsuden* measures.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Peak electricity consumption recorded by TEPCO during the period was 49.22GW, which is 10.77GW (18%) lower than the peak consumption in the previous year.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Overall electricity consumption during July and August was also 14% less than in the previous year.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The peak electricity consumption within TEP's area was 12.46GW during the 2011 summer, 3.11GW (20%) less than the peak consumption in the previous year, and the overall consumption have been reduced by 11% in July with 17% in August compared to previous year.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A 220,000-barrel-per-day (35,000 m3) oil refinery of Cosmo Oil Company was set on fire by the quake at Ichihara, Chiba Prefecture, to the east of Tokyo.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] It was extinguished after ten days, injuring six people, and destroying storage tanks.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Other refineries halted production due to safety checks and power loss.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Sendai, a 145,000-barrel-per-day (23,100 m3) refinery owned by the largest refiner in Japan, JX Nippon Oil & Energy, was also set ablaze by the quake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Workers were evacuated, but tsunami warnings hindered efforts to extinguish the fire until 14 March, when officials planned to do so.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] An analyst estimated that consumption of various types of oil could have increased by as much as 300,000 barrels (48,000 m3) per day (as well as LNG), as back-up power plants burning fossil fuels attempted to compensate for the loss of 11 GW of Japan's nuclear power capacity.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The city-owned plant for importing liquefied natural gas in Sendai was severely damaged, and supplies were halted for at least a month.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In addition to refining and storage, several power plants were damaged.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] These include Sendai #4, New-Sendai #1 and #2, Haranomachi #1 and #2, Hirono #2 and #4 and Hitachinaka #1.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Fukushima Daiichi, Fukushima Daini, Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant and Tōkai nuclear power stations, consisting of a total eleven reactors, were automatically shut down following the earthquake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Higashidōri, also on the northeast coast, was already shut down for a periodic inspection.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Cooling is needed to remove decay heat after a Generation II reactor has been shut down, and to maintain spent fuel pools.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The backup cooling process is powered by emergency diesel generators at the plants and at Rokkasho nuclear reprocessing plant.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] At Fukushima Daiichi and Daini, tsunami waves overtopped seawalls and destroyed diesel backup power systems, leading to severe problems at Fukushima Daiichi, including three large explosions and radioactive leakage.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Subsequent analysis found that many Japanese nuclear plants, including Fukushima Daiichi, were not adequately protected against tsunamis.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The discharge of radioactive water in Fukushima was confirmed in later analysis at the three reactors at Fukushima I (Units 1, 2, and 3), which suffered meltdowns and continued to leak coolant water.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The aftershock on 7 April caused the loss of external power to Rokkasho Reprocessing Plant and Higashidori Nuclear Power Plant but backup generators were functional.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant lost three of its four external power lines and temporarily lost cooling function in its spent fuel pools for "20 to 80 minutes".
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A spill of "up to 3.8 litres [1.0 US gal]" of radioactive water also occurred at Onagawa following the aftershock.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A report by the IAEA in 2012 found that the Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant had remained largely undamaged.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In 2013, only two nuclear reactors in Japan had been restarted since the 2011 shutdowns.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In February 2019, there were 42 operable reactors in Japan.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Of these, only nine reactors in five power plants were operating after having been restarted post-2011.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japan declared a state of emergency following the failure of the cooling system at the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant, resulting in the evacuation of nearby residents.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Officials from the Japanese Nuclear and Industrial Safety Agency reported that radiation levels inside the plant were up to 1,000 times normal levels, and that radiation levels outside the plant were up to eight times normal levels.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Later, a state of emergency was also declared at the Fukushima Daini nuclear power plant about 11 km (6.8 mi) south.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Experts described the Fukushima disaster was not as bad as the Chernobyl disaster, but worse than the Three Mile Island accident.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The discharge of radioactive water of the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant was later detected in tap water.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Radioactive iodine was detected in the tap water in Fukushima, Tochigi, Gunma, Tokyo, Chiba, Saitama, and Niigata, and radioactive caesium in the tap water in Fukushima, Tochigi and Gunma.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Radioactive caesium, iodine, and strontium were also detected in the soil in some places in Fukushima.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There may be a need to replace the contaminated soil.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Many radioactive hotspots were found outside the evacuation zone, including Tokyo.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Radioactive contamination of food products were detected in several places in Japan.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In 2021, the Japanese cabinet finally approved the dumping of radioactive water in Fukushima into the Pacific Ocean over a course of 30 years, with full support of IAEA.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] To this day, the water is still actively being de-contaminated and is scheduled to be completed by the year 2051.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A fire occurred in the turbine section of the Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant following the earthquake.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The blaze was in a building housing the turbine, which is sited separately from the plant's reactor, and was soon extinguished.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The plant was shut down as a precaution.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On 13 March the lowest-level state of emergency was declared regarding the Onagawa plant as radioactivity readings temporarily exceeded allowed levels in the area of the plant.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tōhoku Electric Power Co. stated this may have been due to radiation from the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear accidents but was not from the Onagawa plant itself.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As a result of the 7 April aftershock, Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant lost three of four external power lines and lost cooling function for as much as 80 minutes.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A spill of a couple of litres of radioactive water occurred at Onagawa.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The number 2 reactor at Tōkai Nuclear Power Plant was shut down automatically.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japan's transport network suffered severe disruptions.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Many sections of Tōhoku Expressway serving northern Japan were damaged.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The expressway did not reopen to general public use until 24 March 2011.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All railway services were suspended in Tokyo, with an estimated 20,000 people stranded at major stations across the city.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In the hours after the earthquake, some train services were resumed.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most Tokyo area train lines resumed full service by the next day—12 March.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Twenty thousand stranded visitors spent the night of 11–12 March inside Tokyo Disneyland.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A tsunami flooded Sendai Airport at 15:55 JST, about one hour after the initial quake, causing severe damage.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Narita and Haneda Airport both briefly suspended operations after the quake, but suffered little damage and reopened within 24 hours.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Eleven airliners bound for Narita were diverted to nearby Yokota Air Base.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Various train services around Japan were also canceled, with JR East suspending all services for the rest of the day.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Four trains on coastal lines were reported as being out of contact with operators; one, a four-car train on the Senseki Line, was found to have derailed, and its occupants were rescued shortly after 8 am the next morning.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There were no derailments of Shinkansen bullet train services in and out of Tokyo, but their services were also suspended.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Tokaido Shinkansen resumed limited service late in the day and was back to its normal schedule by the next day, while the Jōetsu and Nagano Shinkansen resumed services late on 12 March.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Services on Yamagata Shinkansen resumed with limited numbers of trains on 31 March.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Derailments were minimized because of an early warning system that detected the earthquake before it struck.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The system automatically stopped all high-speed trains, which minimized the damage.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Tōhoku Shinkansen line was worst hit, with JR East estimating that 1,100 sections of the line, varying from collapsed station roofs to bent power pylons, would need repairs.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Services on the Tōhoku Shinkansen partially resumed only in Kantō area on 15 March, with one round-trip service per hour between Tokyo and Nasu-Shiobara, and Tōhoku area service partially resumed on 22 March between Morioka and Shin-Aomori.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Services on Akita Shinkansen resumed with limited numbers of trains on 18 March.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Service between Tokyo and Shin-Aomori was restored by May, but at lower speeds due to ongoing restoration work; the pre-earthquake timetable was not reinstated until late September.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The rolling blackouts brought on by the crises at the nuclear power plants in Fukushima had a profound effect on the rail networks around Tokyo starting on 14 March.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Major railways began running trains at 10–20 minute intervals, rather than the usual 3–5 minute intervals, operating some lines only at rush hour and completely shutting down others; notably, the Tōkaidō Main Line, Yokosuka Line, Sōbu Main Line and Chūō-Sōbu Line were all stopped for the day.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] This led to near-paralysis within the capital, with long lines at train stations and many people unable to come to work or get home.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Railway operators gradually increased capacity over the next few days, until running at approximately 80% capacity by 17 March and relieving the worst of the passenger congestion.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] (left) and a damaged utility pole in Ishinomaki (right).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Cellular and landline phone service suffered major disruptions in the affected area.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Immediately after the earthquake cellular communication was jammed across much of Japan due to a surge of network activity.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On the day of the quake itself American broadcaster NPR was unable to reach anyone in Sendai with a working phone or access to the Internet.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Internet services were largely unaffected in areas where basic infrastructure remained, despite the earthquake having damaged portions of several undersea cable systems landing in the affected regions; these systems were able to reroute around affected segments onto redundant links.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Within Japan, only a few websites were initially unreachable.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There was no loss of life, although the tsunami resulted in damage to all 18 Mitsubishi F-2 fighter jets of the 21st Fighter Training Squadron.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Twelve of the aircraft were scrapped, while the remaining six were slated for repair at a cost of 80 billion yen ($1 billion), exceeding the original cost of the aircraft.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] After the tsunami, elements of the Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force put to sea without orders and started rescuing those who had been washed out to sea.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tsunami plans were for the Japan Self-Defense Forces assets to be led, directed, and coordinated by local civic governments.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] However, the earthquake destroyed town halls (the seat of local municipal government), police, and fire services in many places, so the military not only had to respond to but also command rescues.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Stone monuments at the UNESCO World Heritage Site: Shrines and Temples of Nikkō were toppled.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Tokyo, there was damage to Koishikawa Kōrakuen, Rikugien, Hamarikyū Onshi Teien, and the walls of Edo Castle.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Information on the condition of collections held by museums, libraries and archives is still incomplete.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There was no damage to the Historic Monuments and Sites of Hiraizumi in Iwate Prefecture, and the recommendation for their inscription on the UNESCO World Heritage List in June was seized upon as a symbol of international recognition and recovery.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The aftermath of the earthquake and tsunami included a humanitarian crisis and a major economic impact.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami resulted in over 340,000 displaced people in the Tōhoku region, and shortages of food, water, shelter, medicine, and fuel for survivors.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In response, the Japanese government mobilized the Self-Defense Forces (under Joint Task Force – Tōhoku, led by Lieutenant General Eiji Kimizuka), while many countries sent search and rescue teams to help search for survivors.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Aid organizations in Japan and worldwide responded, with the Japanese Red Cross reporting $1 billion in donations.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The economic impact included immediate problems, with industrial production suspended in many factories, and the longer term issue of the cost of rebuilding, which has been estimated at ¥10 trillion ($122 billion).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In comparison to the 1995 Great Hanshin earthquake, the East Japan earthquake brought serious damage to an extremely wide range.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The aftermath of the twin disasters left Japan's coastal cities and towns with nearly 25 million tons of debris.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Ishinomaki alone, there were 17 trash collection sites 180 meters (590 ft) long and at least 4.5 meters (15 ft) high.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] An official in the city's government trash disposal department estimated that it would take three years to empty these sites.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In April 2015, authorities off the coast of Oregon discovered debris that was thought to be from a boat destroyed during the tsunami.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The cargo contained yellowtail amberjack, a species of fish that lives off the coast of Japan, still alive.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] KGW estimates that more than 1 million tons of debris still remain in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In February 2016, a memorial was inaugurated by two architects for the victims of the disaster, consisting of a 6.5-square-metre (70 sq ft) structure on a hillside between a temple and a cherry tree in Ishinomaki.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The reconstruction of the Tohoku coast was funded and piloted by the Japanese government.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Structural adaptation to tsunamis was largely based on building higher seawalls, although seawalls proved largely ineffective in 2011, and the new seawalls would also not have been high enough.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Seismologists anticipated a very large quake would strike in the same place as the 1923 Great Kantō earthquake—in the Sagami Trough, southwest of Tokyo.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Japanese government had tracked plate movements since 1976 in preparation for the so-called Tokai earthquake, predicted to take place in that region.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] However, occurring as it did 373 km (232 mi) north east of Tokyo, the Tōhoku earthquake came as a surprise to seismologists.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] While the Japan Trench was known for creating large quakes, it had not been expected to generate quakes above an 8.0 magnitude.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Also, a tsunami-earthquake with a tsunami magnitude scales (Mt) between 8.6 and 9.0 (Similar to the 1896 Sanriku earthquake, the Mt for the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake was 9.1–9.4) had a 30% chance to occur within 30 years.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The quake gave scientists the opportunity to collect a large amount of data to model the seismic events that took place in great detail.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] This data is expected to be used in a variety of ways, providing unprecedented information about how buildings respond to shaking, and other effects.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Gravimetric data from the quake have been used to create a model for increased warning time compared to seismic models, as gravity fields travel faster than seismic waves.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Researchers have also analysed the economic effects of this earthquake and have developed models of the nationwide propagation via interfirm supply networks of the shock that originated in the Tōhoku region.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] After the full extent of the disaster was known, researchers soon launched a project to gather all digital material relating to the disaster into an online searchable archive to form the basis of future research into the events during and after the disaster.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Japan Disasters Digital Archive is presented in English and Japanese and is hosted at the Reischauer Institute of Japanese Studies at Harvard University in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Some of the first research to come from the archive was a 2014 paper from the Digital Methods Initiative in Amsterdam about patterns of Twitter usage around the time of the disaster.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] At this time Japan's Disaster Management Office (Naikakufu Bosai Keikaku) published a bi-lingual guide in Japanese and English, *Disaster Management in Japan*, to outline the several varieties of natural disaster and the preparations being made for the eventuality of each.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Japan Trench Fast Drilling Project, a scientific expedition conducted in 2012–2013, drilled ocean-floor boreholes through the fault zone of the earthquake and gathered important data about the rupture mechanism and physical properties of the fault that caused the 2011 earthquake and tsunami.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami had a great environmental impact on Japan's eastern coast.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The rarity and magnitude of the earthquake-tsunami prompted researchers Jotaro Urabe, Takao Suzuki, Tatsuki Nishita, and Wataru Makino to study their immediate ecological impacts on intertidal flat communities at Sendai Bay and the Sanriku Ria coast.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Pre- and post-event surveys show a reduction in animal taxon richness and change in taxon composition mainly attributed to the tsunami and its physical impacts.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In particular, sessile epibenthic animals and endobenthic animals both decreased in taxon richness.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Mobile epibenthic animals, such as hermit crabs, were not as affected.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Post-surveys also recorded taxa that were not previously recorded before, suggesting that tsunamis have the potential to introduce species and change taxon composition and local community structure.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The long term ecological impacts at Sendai Bay and the greater east coast of Japan require further study.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/agility-trains] The consortium's bid was centered around the Class 800 and 801 high speed trains, which provided more seats, reduced journey times, and superior environmental performance than the Intercity 125 sets.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/agility-trains] The bid submitted by the consortium was successful, leading to the finalising of a £4.5bn contract in mid 2012 to produce and sustain trains for both the Great Western Main Line (GWML) and East Coast Main Line (ECML).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/agility-trains] Infrastructure built to fulfil the contract included a new manufacturing site at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe and multiple new depots to maintain the fleet.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/agility-trains] In October 2017, the first train went into service on the GWML.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/agility-trains] Agility Trains was formed in response to the Intercity Express Programme (IEP), launched by the Department for Transport (DfT) in 2005 with the initial goal of procuring a replacement for the aging Intercity 125 fleet on both the Great Western Main Line and East Coast Main Line.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/agility-trains] On 16 November 2007, the DfT issued an Invitation to Tender for the IEP to three shortlisted entities: Alstom-Barclays Rail Group; Express Rail Alliance (Bombardier, Siemens, Angel Trains and Babcock & Brown); and Agility Trains.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/agility-trains] Shortly after Alstom's decision to withdraw from the bidding in February 2008, British investment firm Barclays Private Equity opted to re-enter the IEP on 26 June 2008, four days before the end of the bidding process, as a partner of Hitachi and John Laing, in Agility Trains.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/agility-trains] The finalised £4.5bn contract for trains for the GWML and ECML was announced in July 2012.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/agility-trains] Assembly of most of the trains took place in the UK, using Japanese-built bodyshells, with a new factory being established at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/agility-trains] Additionally, new depots to maintain the new train fleet were also developed.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/agility-trains] The first IEP train left the Kasado factory on 7 January 2015 for shipping via Kobe, In October 2017, the first train went into service on the Great Western Main Line.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/agility-trains] In May 2019, the first train entered service on the East Coast Main Line between London King's Cross and Leeds.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/agility-trains] Several ownership changes took place during the late 2010s and early 2020s. in March 2018, Axa announced that it would purchase half of John Laing Group's shareholding in the consortium.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/agility-trains] In September 2020, John Laing Group announced that it was selling its remaining stake in Agility Trains to AIP Management in exchange for £421 million in cash.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/agility-trains] In November 2021, GLIL Infrastructure purchased a 30% stake in Agility Trains from Hitachi; as a result, Hitachi's stake dropped to 40 percent while GLIL and AIP owning a 30% stake each.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/alaxala-networks] In 2004, Alaxala Networks Corp. was originally established, as the merger between Hitachi and NEC networking hardware divisions.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/alaxala-networks] The name of **Alaxala** was derived from "ALL Access for eXpert and Latent Association", and more that "Ala" in Latin means "Wing", and "X" means "networking eXchange", so the company intended the two "Ala" (Hitachi and NEC) connected and collaborated by "X" tightly.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/alaxala-networks] The company is basically fabless company, designing the products, mostly ordering to manufacture them to Hitachi enterprise servers division factory in Hadano, Kanagawa, Japan.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/alaxala-networks] The company offers networking hardware products, network router and network switch etc.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/alaxala-networks] Alaxala products are sold and installed mostly in Japanese domestic market and for enterprises, but we can find several products at some online shopping, Amazon.com etc..
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/alaxala-networks] The business type and scope is same as Allied Telesis, that is also the company in Japan.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/alaxala-networks] And they are collaborated for producing networking hardware sold in both brands.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/alaxala-networks] Alaxala official agencies are Hitachi, NEC, Itochu Techno-Solutions, Net One Systems, and Alaxala has contributed to offer the various networking hardware products to major communication companies in Japan, such as NTT, KDDI, Softbank, and others.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/alaxala-networks] On August 24, 2012, Alaxala was known that Tokyo Stock Exchange (TSE) announced that TSE core system outage happened due to the software bugs on Alaxala networking hardware.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/alaxala-networks] Alaxala also sponsors IT professional certifications for Alaxala products, like Cisco, Oracle, and others.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] Ami has a Humid continental climate (Köppen *Cfa*) characterized by warm summers and cool winters with light snowfall.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] The average annual temperature in Ami is 13.8 °C.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] The average annual rainfall is 1306 mm with September as the wettest month.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] The temperatures are highest on average in August, at around 25.7 °C, and lowest in January, at around 2.8 °C.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] Per Japanese census data, the population of Ami has recently plateaued after a long period of growth.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] During the Edo period, the area around Ami was part of Hitachi Province.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] The villages of Ami, Kimihara, Asahi and Funashima were created with the establishment of the modern municipalities system on April 1, 1889.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] In 1921, the Imperial Japanese Navy established Kasumigaura Air Field, a naval aviation training base at Ami, with floatplane operations on nearby Kasumigaura.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] Zeppelin operations also began from 1929.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] In 1937, the Youth Aviation Squadron was transferred from Yokosuka.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] The base was repeatedly bombed in 1944 and 1945 during World War II, with the attack on June 10, 1945, killing over 300 people.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] On April 1, 1955, the villages of Ami, Kimihara and Asahi merged to form the town of Ami.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] Most of the village of Funashima joined on April 20, 1955.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] Ami has a mayor-council form of government with a directly elected mayor and a unicameral town council of 18 members.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] Ami contributes one member to the Ibaraki Prefectural Assembly.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] In terms of national politics, the town is part of Ibaraki 6th district of the lower house of the Diet of Japan.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] Agriculture remains predominant; however, there are also numerous factories for chemicals, light manufacturing and electronics.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/ami-ibaraki] The Japanese Ground Self-Defense Force also has a number of military installations in the town.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] The company name was changed from **Hitachi Astemo, Ltd.** to Astemo, Ltd. on April 1, 2025.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] Astemo was established in January 2021 as a global automotive components manufacturer through the business merger of Hitachi Automotive Systems, Keihin Corporation, Showa Corporation, and Nissin Kogyo.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] The name "Astemo" stands for "Advanced Sustainable Technologies for Mobility", reflecting the company's focus on technologies related to connected, autonomous, shared and electric mobility.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] Astemo develops automotive technologies aligned with the industry trends of connectivity, autonomous systems and electrification, with a focus on both passenger and motorcycle applications.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] Astemo's ownership structure includes major stakes from both Hitachi, Ltd. and Honda Motor Co., Ltd., each holding 40%, with JIC Capital holding the remaining 20%.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] While Astemo includes former Honda-affiliated parts manufacturers, it also maintains business relationships with Nissan Motor Co., reflecting Hitachi's historical ties to the Nissan Group.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] In December 2025, Honda announced it would acquire an additional 21% of Astemo shares from Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] As a result, the shareholding structure of Astemo will change to 61% for Honda, 20% for JIC, and 19% for Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] Astemo has expanded its research and development activities in electric powertrains, advanced driver-assistance systems, and in-vehicle software.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] These efforts support its strategic focus on electrification and autonomous mobility.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] The company has also pursued partnerships and vertical integration to address industry competition and supply chain challenges.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] In December 2024, the Government of Cantabria awarded the Hitachi Astemo Buelna plant a €1 million grant through SODERCAN’s competitive programme for major industrial competitiveness projects.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] The funding supports a €5 million experimental development project focused on advanced braking systems, to be completed over 18 months.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] This initiative underlines the region’s strategic support for automotive innovation and sustainability efforts.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] Astemo develops components for electric and autonomous vehicles, with a focus on integration of key systems such as power control units, motors, inverters, and software-defined vehicle platforms.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] The company also emphasizes model-based systems engineering and virtual validation to shorten development timelines and reduce prototyping costs.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] In 2023, Astemo announced a ¥15.3 billion (~US $100 million) expansion of its Berea, Kentucky plant to support its electrification business.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] In July 2025, Astemo announced a £100 million investment in its Horwich manufacturing facility in Bolton, Greater Manchester.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] The project will establish a new production line dedicated to electric vehicle (EV) inverters, making the site the only facility in the United Kingdom with this production capability.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] As of 2025, Astemo operates over 100 business sites globally, including manufacturing plants, R&D centers and regional offices across Asia, Europe and the Americas.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] Astemo's facilities span over 25 countries, including sites in Mexico, France, Brazil, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] A complete list is available on the Astemo Global Network.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] In September 2025, *CBS News* and *The Detroit News* reported that Astemo planned to establish a regional headquarters in Wixom, Michigan, as part of a $95 million investment expected to create about 200 jobs.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] Hitachi Astemo sponsors Team Penske in NTT IndyCar Series in the U.S.A.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] Astemo also sponsors Real Racing in the Super GT GT500 class and S.I.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] RACING in the MFJ All Japan Road Race Championship Series.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] Astemo owns the Japanese women's volleyball team "Hitachi Astemo Rivale" and sponsors Mie Honda Heat, a Japanese rugby union team based in Suzuka City.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] On December 21, 2021, Hitachi Astemo admitted to falsifying inspection data on brake and suspension components.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/astemo] Over 50,000 instances of improper testing were identified, dating back to 2003.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] Bandō is located in far southwestern Ibaraki Prefecture, on the north bank of the Tone River, bordered by Chiba Prefecture to the southwest.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] It is approximately 50 kilometers northeast of Tokyo.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] Bandō has a Humid continental climate (Köppen *Cfa*) characterized by warm summers and cool winters with light snowfall.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] The average annual temperature in Bandō is 14.3 °C.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] The average annual rainfall is 1316 mm with September as the wettest month.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] The temperatures are highest on average in August, at around 26.4 °C, and lowest in January, at around 3.2 °C.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] Per Japanese census data, the population of Bandō peaked around the year 1990 and has declined slightly since.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] The area of modern Bandō was part of Shimōsa Province until the start of the Meiji period.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] With the establishment of the modern municipalities system on April 1, 1889, the village of Iwai was created within Sashima District, Ibaraki.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] Iwai was elevated to town status on July 4, 1900, and to city status on April 1, 1972.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] The city of Bandō was established on March 22, 2005, from the merger of the city of Iwai with the neighboring town of Sashima.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] Bandō has a mayor-council form of government with a directly elected mayor and a unicameral city council of 20 members.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] Bandō contributes one member to the Ibaraki Prefectural Assembly.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] In terms of national politics, the city is part of Ibaraki 7th district of the lower house of the Diet of Japan.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] Bandō has mixed economy with a large number of industrial parks.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/bandō-ibaraki] The area is traditionally known for its production of leeks, lettuce and Chinese cabbage.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] Located in northern Ibaraki Prefecture, Hitachi has a long coast along the Pacific Ocean to the east.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] Japan National Route 6 runs in parallel with the coast, connecting Tokyo and Sendai, and develops residential and commercial areas in the relatively narrow land of the coastal plain.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] Geologically the city covers Cambrian basement, some 500 million years old, with marble being quarried in the west for manufacturing cement material.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] Hitachi has a Humid continental climate (Köppen *Cfa*) characterized by warm summers and cold winters with heavy snowfall.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] The average annual temperature in Hitachi is 14.3 °C (57.7 °F).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] The average annual rainfall is 1,455.7 mm (57.31 in) with October as the wettest month.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] The temperatures are highest on average in August, at around 25.0 °C (77.0 °F), and lowest in January, at around 4.6 °C (40.3 °F).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] Per Japanese census data, the population of Hitachi peaked around 1980 and has steadily declined since.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] Human settlement in the Hitachi area dates to at least the Japanese Paleolithic period.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] In the early Nara period, the area was defined as part of Taga Province, which was then merged into Hitachi Province under the *Ritsuryō* system.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] By the Sengoku period, the area was under the control of the Satake clan.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] Following the creation of the Tokugawa shogunate, Tokugawa Ieyasu ordered the Satake to Dewa Province, and the area became part of the domain's awarded to Ieyasu's son Tokugawa Yorifusa.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] The area remained part of Mito Domain until the Meiji restoration.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] The village of Hitachi was formed on April 1, 1889 with the establishment of the modern municipalities system.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] The area rapidly developed towards the end of the Meiji period under the direction of Fusanosuke Kuhara of the Kuhara zaibatsu with the opening of copper mines, and under Namihei Odaira, the founder of Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] The village of Hitachi was raised to town status on August 26, 1924.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] Hitachi and the neighboring town of Sukegawa merged on September 1, 1939, to form the city of Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] The city suffered from major damage in World War II, from shore bombardment by the United States Navy on July 17, 1945, and in air raids on June 10 and July 19.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] Hitachi was an important military target, as it was a major industrial center, which containing numerous factories of the Hitachi *zaibatsu*, especially connected with the production of electrical equipment.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] It also had a copper mine that contained 1/10 of all of Japan's copper.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] Following an air raid on June 10 by the USAAF, which missed the Hitachi factories and burned down much of the civilian residential districts, the city was subjected to shore bombardment on July 19 by the battleships USS *Iowa* (BB-61), USS *Missouri* (BB-63), and USS *Wisconsin* (BB-64).
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] However, the bombardment was very inaccurate, and although civilian casualties were very high, the Hitachi factories were again largely left intact.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] The shore bombardment was followed by a second air raid with incendiary bombs on July 19.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] In 1976 the disassembled MiG-25 fighter jet that Soviet pilot Viktor Belenko had defected in was returned to the Soviet Union from the port of Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] It had been extensively examined at the nearby Hyakuri Air Base.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] The borders of Hitachi expanded in 1955–1956 through the annexation of the neighboring villages of Hidaka, Sakamoto, Higashiosawa, Nakasato, Toyoura, the towns of Taga and Kuji.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] On November 1, 2004, the neighboring town of Jūō (from Taga District) was merged into Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] The city suffered from minor damage in the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami with no fatalities reported.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] Hitachi has a mayor-council form of government with a directly elected mayor and a unicameral city council of 28 members.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] Hitachi contributes five members to the Ibaraki Prefectural Assembly.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] In terms of national politics, the city is part of Ibaraki 5th district of the lower house of the Diet of Japan.
[src:hitachi-ibaraki/hitachi-ibaraki] Hitachi is a major industrial center, and is the former location of the headquarters of Hitachi and various of its group companies.
